1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,290
What about me? This is murder.

2
00:00:00,300 --> 00:00:02,130
What about Scotland Yard?

3
00:00:02,130 --> 00:00:04,550
What about Sherlock Holmes?

4
00:00:04,550 --> 00:00:06,660
Now get out!

5
00:00:33,410 --> 00:00:35,480
Did you get it?

6
00:00:37,290 --> 00:00:38,750
Good.

7
00:00:38,750 --> 00:00:41,790
Did you have any
trouble with him?

8
00:00:41,800 --> 00:00:43,910
Just a matter of murder.

9
00:00:47,680 --> 00:00:49,970
- Ah, Mr. Holmes.
- Hopkins.

10
00:00:49,970 --> 00:00:51,550
Thanks for coming so promptly.

11
00:00:51,560 --> 00:00:54,640
Inspector Lestrade suggested
that I call through to you.

12
00:00:54,640 --> 00:00:58,060
- Mr. Emery was a client of Mr. Holmes, Inspector.
- Indeed.

13
00:00:58,060 --> 00:01:00,060
You didn't mention that when
I telephoned you, Mr. Holmes.

14
00:01:00,060 --> 00:01:02,060
Well not exactly
a client, Inspector.

15
00:01:02,070 --> 00:01:04,730
- Sergeant Thompson?
- He was killed between the hours of eleven

16
00:01:04,740 --> 00:01:07,580
and two o'clock this
morning, Mr. Holmes.

17
00:01:09,240 --> 00:01:10,520
Must have been someone he knew.

18
00:01:10,530 --> 00:01:13,330
Someone of whom
he had no suspicion.

19
00:01:13,330 --> 00:01:15,080
Poor old Stinky.

20
00:01:15,080 --> 00:01:17,750
It's all my fault.
I should have prevented this.

21
00:01:17,750 --> 00:01:21,330
Well, it's no time to start
talking about that now, Doctor.

22
00:01:21,340 --> 00:01:23,130
Apparently, it's gone.

23
00:01:23,130 --> 00:01:25,130
That's the second attempt
on the musical box

24
00:01:25,130 --> 00:01:26,920
that Emery bought
at the auction sale

25
00:01:26,920 --> 00:01:28,720
and this time it was successful.

26
00:01:28,720 --> 00:01:30,510
But that box is only
worth two pounds.

27
00:01:30,510 --> 00:01:32,760
It's worth a man's life, Watson.

28
00:01:32,760 --> 00:01:36,180
I think we'd better pay a visit to Gaylord's
Auction Room and that fellow Crabtree.

29
00:01:36,180 --> 00:01:37,560
Inspector may I suggest

30
00:01:37,560 --> 00:01:39,350
that you make a complete
search of this flat

31
00:01:39,350 --> 00:01:43,060
for a small plain musical
box about that size.

32
00:01:43,070 --> 00:01:45,040
Thank you. Come on, Watson.

33
00:01:46,780 --> 00:01:49,450
You say the first box
went to Mr. Julian Emery,

34
00:01:49,450 --> 00:01:52,780
the second, Mr. Kilgour,
143B Hampton Way,

35
00:01:52,780 --> 00:01:54,660
and the third to the
unidentified young lady

36
00:01:54,660 --> 00:01:56,910
who presumably has a shop
and lives near Golders Green?

37
00:01:56,910 --> 00:01:58,240
That's right Mr. Holmes.

38
00:01:58,250 --> 00:02:00,660
Isn't it rather strange,
Mr. Crabtree,

39
00:02:00,670 --> 00:02:03,790
that you've had three identical musical
boxes, all playing the same tune?

40
00:02:03,790 --> 00:02:05,710
- Where did they come from?
- Dartmoor Prison.

41
00:02:05,710 --> 00:02:08,800
- Dartmoor?
- We get a regular shipment from there every month.

42
00:02:08,800 --> 00:02:10,170
The inmates manufacture them.

43
00:02:10,180 --> 00:02:11,510
Well, they make all kinds
of things you know?

44
00:02:11,510 --> 00:02:13,180
Pipe racks, wastepaper baskets,

45
00:02:13,180 --> 00:02:15,640
- musical boxes.
- Did you happen to notice

46
00:02:15,640 --> 00:02:18,770
if anyone showed any particular
interest during the auction

47
00:02:18,770 --> 00:02:22,730
in the purchases
of these three boxes?

48
00:02:22,730 --> 00:02:24,480
Oh, come now, Mr. Crabtree,

49
00:02:24,480 --> 00:02:26,900
this is very literally a
matter of life and death.

50
00:02:26,900 --> 00:02:29,280
Well, since you put it
that way, Mr. Holmes,

51
00:02:29,280 --> 00:02:31,570
there was a gentleman came in here
about an hour after closing time.

52
00:02:31,570 --> 00:02:35,530
And he was in an
awful state, he was,

53
00:02:35,530 --> 00:02:37,620
he gave me five pounds to tell
him where the boxes had gone.

54
00:02:37,620 --> 00:02:39,620
He said they had sentimental
value for him, sir.

55
00:02:39,620 --> 00:02:41,500
Expensive sentiment.

56
00:02:41,500 --> 00:02:42,740
Can you describe him?

57
00:02:42,750 --> 00:02:44,290
Well he was tall,
distinguished looking

58
00:02:44,290 --> 00:02:46,210
and he had gray hair
and a mustache.

59
00:02:46,210 --> 00:02:47,500
He was quite a gentleman, sir.

60
00:02:47,500 --> 00:02:49,050
And what was his reaction

61
00:02:49,050 --> 00:02:50,840
when you were
unable to supply him

62
00:02:50,840 --> 00:02:52,720
with the address of the young
lady who owned the shop?

63
00:02:52,720 --> 00:02:55,220
I told him that the young lady
usually come back on Thursday.

64
00:02:55,220 --> 00:02:57,930
He said he'd come back on
Thursday and that's tomorrow.

65
00:02:57,930 --> 00:03:00,680
Thank you Mr. Crabtree, you've
been very helpful. Thank you.

66
00:03:00,680 --> 00:03:02,270
Come along, Watson.

67
00:03:02,270 --> 00:03:04,480
- Where we going now, Holmes?
- The home of Mr. Kilgour,

68
00:03:04,480 --> 00:03:06,270
the man who bought
the third box.

69
00:03:12,530 --> 00:03:14,450
But hang it all, Holmes,

70
00:03:14,450 --> 00:03:16,530
how do you know those other two
musical boxes are of any importance?

71
00:03:16,530 --> 00:03:18,030
I don't, but I certainly
have no intention

72
00:03:18,030 --> 00:03:20,840
of waiting till the owners
are murdered to find out.

73
00:03:22,750 --> 00:03:24,210
No one at home.

74
00:03:24,210 --> 00:03:26,500
I hope that's the explanation.

75
00:03:26,500 --> 00:03:28,660
Well, have a look
through this window.

76
00:03:33,840 --> 00:03:36,930
Doesn't seem to be anyone there.

77
00:03:36,930 --> 00:03:40,810
Whole place seems deserted
as far as I can see.

78
00:03:40,810 --> 00:03:43,350
- Yes?
- Mr. and Mrs. Kilgour at home?

79
00:03:43,350 --> 00:03:44,980
- No.
- When do you expect them?

80
00:03:44,980 --> 00:03:46,980
Oh, in an hour or so.

81
00:03:46,980 --> 00:03:48,650
There's no use
you're hanging about.

82
00:03:48,650 --> 00:03:50,270
They don't buy nothing
from peddlers.

83
00:03:50,280 --> 00:03:51,560
Peddlers?

84
00:03:51,570 --> 00:03:53,610
My good woman this is
Mr. Sherlock Holmes.

85
00:03:53,610 --> 00:03:55,570
Sherlock Holmes? Oh, go on.

86
00:03:55,570 --> 00:03:57,620
Do you mind if we
come in and wait?

87
00:03:57,620 --> 00:03:58,990
My business is rather urgent.

88
00:03:58,990 --> 00:04:01,950
Well, I've got to go out
to do my shopping

89
00:04:01,950 --> 00:04:03,580
and I don't know if Mrs. Kilgour

90
00:04:03,580 --> 00:04:05,580
would like any strangers
nosing about.

91
00:04:05,580 --> 00:04:07,170
Quite all right, I assure you.

92
00:04:07,170 --> 00:04:08,670
Well, I've got to be off.

93
00:04:08,670 --> 00:04:12,170
You two wait in the parlor
and no smoking either.

94
00:04:12,170 --> 00:04:17,130
Mrs. Kilgour says it
smells up the house.

95
00:04:17,140 --> 00:04:19,700
- Funny old girl, Holmes.
- Hmm.

96
00:04:37,160 --> 00:04:39,200
- Park Lane.
- Park Lane?

97
00:04:39,200 --> 00:04:41,370
And what would the likes of
you be doing in Park Lane?

98
00:04:41,370 --> 00:04:43,330
Now don't worry
about the fare, ducky.

99
00:04:43,330 --> 00:04:46,360
If ya knows how to get
to Park Lane, now off it.

100
00:04:51,460 --> 00:04:53,590
You know, Holmes,
I've been thinking.

101
00:04:53,590 --> 00:04:54,640
There must have been
something hidden

102
00:04:54,670 --> 00:04:57,420
in that box of old Stinky's.

103
00:04:57,430 --> 00:05:00,800
Stolen jewelry possibly.

104
00:05:00,800 --> 00:05:03,190
- What's up Holmes?
- Listen.

105
00:05:05,350 --> 00:05:08,060
Well, it's just the steam
in the water pipes.

106
00:05:13,860 --> 00:05:15,230
Watson!

107
00:05:17,400 --> 00:05:19,010
Great Scott!

108
00:05:20,410 --> 00:05:22,880
Come along, Holmes,
get her on the chair here.

109
00:05:23,700 --> 00:05:26,410
Shh. It's all right, my dear.

110
00:05:27,460 --> 00:05:30,750
There, there, there.
Now don't worry.

111
00:05:30,750 --> 00:05:32,750
It's all over.

112
00:05:32,750 --> 00:05:35,050
There you are, dear.
Don't cry anymore.

113
00:05:35,050 --> 00:05:37,840
She tied me up and
shut me in the cupboard.

114
00:05:37,840 --> 00:05:39,680
I know, I know.

115
00:05:39,680 --> 00:05:41,590
She won't come back.

116
00:05:41,600 --> 00:05:43,720
Did you show her
your new musical box?

117
00:05:43,720 --> 00:05:46,350
Yes. She said she
wanted to hear it play

118
00:05:46,350 --> 00:05:50,100
- and as soon as I showed it to her she grabbed a hold...
- I know. I know now.

119
00:05:50,100 --> 00:05:52,350
Now don't worry, we'll buy
you a new musical box.

120
00:05:52,360 --> 00:05:54,610
Yes, my dear,
the best one in London.

121
00:05:54,610 --> 00:05:56,780
Watson.

122
00:05:56,780 --> 00:05:58,940
Oh, what a fool,
what a fool I've been.

123
00:05:58,950 --> 00:06:00,280
What do you mean, Holmes?

124
00:06:00,280 --> 00:06:01,470
She took the musical box
out of this house

125
00:06:01,490 --> 00:06:03,070
in that market basket

126
00:06:03,070 --> 00:06:04,830
right under our very noses.

127
00:06:04,830 --> 00:06:08,000
Why would the Kilgour charwoman
want to take the music box?

128
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:09,580
She isn't the Kilgour charwoman

129
00:06:09,580 --> 00:06:11,460
she's a consummate actress.

130
00:06:11,460 --> 00:06:13,880
An extremely clever, unscrupulous
woman who will stop at nothing.

131
00:06:13,880 --> 00:06:15,250
Take care of the child,
will you, old fellow,

132
00:06:15,250 --> 00:06:17,000
till her parents get back.

133
00:06:17,010 --> 00:06:19,300
- Explain everything to them.
- Of course I will.

134
00:06:19,300 --> 00:06:21,180
But Holmes, where are you going?

135
00:06:21,180 --> 00:06:22,970
Somewhere, somehow

136
00:06:22,970 --> 00:06:25,300
I must get to the young lady who
bought that third musical box

137
00:06:25,310 --> 00:06:27,010
before our opponents find her.

138
00:06:27,020 --> 00:06:29,450
I only hope that
I won't be too late.

139
00:06:34,770 --> 00:06:38,070
Now, now, now, darling
you mustn't cry anymore.

140
00:06:38,070 --> 00:06:39,400
Cheer up.

141
00:06:39,400 --> 00:06:41,570
Would you... would you
like to hear old uncle

142
00:06:41,570 --> 00:06:44,000
make a noise like a duck?

143
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:55,250
Oh, sorry. Huh.

144
00:07:20,190 --> 00:07:22,240
Now, ladies and gentlemen
how much am I offered

145
00:07:22,240 --> 00:07:26,370
for this beautiful laced
Dresden china figurine?

146
00:07:26,370 --> 00:07:28,240
A lady of the French court.

147
00:07:28,240 --> 00:07:31,450
Now this is the genuine article.

148
00:07:31,450 --> 00:07:33,540
What a beautiful ornament
for your mantelpiece

149
00:07:33,540 --> 00:07:36,210
as a centerpiece on
the dining room table.

150
00:07:36,210 --> 00:07:38,290
Now will somebody
start me for ten pounds?

151
00:07:38,290 --> 00:07:40,300
Will somebody start me
for ten pounds?

152
00:07:40,300 --> 00:07:42,050
Eight pounds?

153
00:07:42,050 --> 00:07:43,510
Seven pounds?

154
00:07:43,510 --> 00:07:44,840
All right five.

155
00:07:44,840 --> 00:07:45,760
Five pounds is offered.
Five pounds is offered.

156
00:07:45,800 --> 00:07:46,810
Five pounds is offered.

157
00:07:46,850 --> 00:07:48,130
Five pounds ten.

158
00:07:48,140 --> 00:07:51,560
Five pounds fifteen,
five pounds fifteen.

159
00:07:51,560 --> 00:07:53,520
Six pounds is offered.
Six pounds, six pounds,

160
00:07:53,520 --> 00:07:55,230
going once, going twice,

161
00:07:55,230 --> 00:07:57,020
the third and the last call
we're all done.

162
00:07:57,020 --> 00:07:59,540
Sold to the lady from
Trikland for six pounds.
